Currently the export format (1.0.4), defines a global map of libraries keyed by org,name,rev:
```json
{
  "libraries": {
    "org.example:foo:1.0.0" : {
      "default": "jar/path/a.jar",
      "sources": "jar/path/a-sources.jar",
      "javadoc": "jar/path/a-javadoc.jar",
      "tests": "jar/path/a-tests.jar",
    }
  }
}
```

That map is a reflection of the global resolve.
This map is then refernced from dependee targets like so:
```json
{
  "targets": {
    "my/java/library:target": {
      "libraries": [
        "org.example:foo:1.0.0"
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

This is problematic when a given coodinate - org,name,rev - exports multiple _conflicting_ artifacts.  The example above is almost certainly not conflicting, but @ericzundel noted [here](https://rbcommons.com/s/twitter/r/2823/diff/1/?file=2434338#file2434338line214) that such things do exist in the wild.

As such, the export format should be updated to at least separate the primary artifact and it's standard sources and javadoc attachments from subsidary artifacts, ie:
```json
{
  "libraries": {
    "org.example:foo::1.0.0" : {
      "default": "jar/path/a.jar",
      "sources": "jar/path/a-sources.jar",
      "javadoc": "jar/path/a-javadoc.jar"
    },
    "org.example:foo:tests:1.0.0": {
      "tests": "jar/path/a-tests.jar"
    }
  }
}
```

This way a target could refer to either "org.example:foo::1.0.0" or "org.example:foo:tests:1.0.0".

It may make sense though to fully denormalize the "standard" sources and javadoc attachments and let consumers normalize according to their needs, ie:
```json
{
  "libraries": {
    "org.example:foo::1.0.0": "jar/path/a.jar",
    "org.example:foo:sources:1.0.0": "jar/path/a-sources.jar",
    "org.example:foo:javadoc:1.0.0": "jar/path/a-javadoc.jar",
    "org.example:foo:tests:1.0.0": "jar/path/a-tests.jar"
  }
}
```

