Hi! I noticed that attempts to call bind'ed base class functions without binding the base class lead to an error. Its looks like Python expecting the base-type object instead of descendent one (see error log below). I guess this could be 'fixed' by binding lambda functions for such cases but it would be nice if that would not be necessary.

Thanks,

```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

class Base
{
public:
	void foo_base() {}
};

class C : public Base
{
public:
	void foo_c() {}
};
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");

	pybind11::class_<C> cl(m, "C");
	cl.def(pybind11::init<>());

	cl.def("foo_c", &C::foo_c); // calling this works fine!
	cl.def("foo_base", &C::foo_base);  // calling this lead to an error!

    return m.ptr();
}
```


ipython log:
```
In [1]: c = C()
In [2]: c.foo_base()

TypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-2-9bea0f40fb1f> in <module>()
----> 1 c.foo_base()

TypeError: Incompatible function arguments. The following argument types are supported:
    1. (Base) -> NoneType
```

A const object returned by a function should not be mutable from Python. Currently this is not the case if the function / method returns a `shared_ptr<const T>`.
Specifically, changing the attribute `.value` should not be allowed on an object returned by `.get_const()` in the following example, but it is.

    #include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
    
    class Test {
    public:
        explicit Test(int v) : value{v} {};
        int value {};
    
        std::shared_ptr<Test const> get_const() {
            static std::shared_ptr<Test const> instance(new Test(1));
            return instance;
        }
    };
    
    namespace py = pybind11;
    
    PYBIND11_DECLARE_HOLDER_TYPE(T, std::shared_ptr<T>);
    
    PYBIND11_PLUGIN(const_test) {
        py::module m("const_test");
    
        py::class_<Test, std::shared_ptr<Test>>(m, "Test")
            .def(py::init<int>())
            .def("get_const", &Test::get_const)
            .def_readwrite("value", &Test::value);
    
        return m.ptr();
    }

